{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b52a7360-3d9a-4d6f-852b-caa7a6818dc3","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect the trace (30s example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:00:30\n```\n\n**4. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** in Visual Studio, PerfView, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app) (use `--format speedscope` for the latter).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools (distroless image), use **`dotnet-monitor`** as a sidecar instead.\n- For production, prefer `--duration` over interactive stop to avoid forgetting and generating huge traces.\n- `dotnet-trace` has low overhead (~5%) compared to `perf` or `strace`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"74f86e6f-3038-49c7-97d8-f5ada604fa29","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I can answer this from knowledge without needing to search files.","outputTokens":387,"requestId":"D81F:1D44F2:8608EB:9A5964:69FBEAF5"},"id":"04e38c57-93c3-4ed5-9872-2816a882a26e","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:29:36.213Z","parentId":"81031a8a-5bf0-4752-8ac6-aff2438ae9eb"}
